svg.title: An On-the-Fly Reference-Counting Garbage Collector for Java - Yossi Levanoni, Erez Petrank

cc:Work.dc:title: An On-the-Fly Reference-Counting Garbage Collector for Java - Yossi Levanoni, Erez Petrank
cc:Work.dc:description: Presented in the Concurrency and Memory Management Seminar

text.tspan: How to build an efficient reference counting
garbage collector for multi processor systems?
Root reference change more often than heap references
Solution: do not count root references
Record all updated slots, skip unnecessary operations
update all reference counts according to the records
record all slots which are updated
if slot is not dirty then
write new object to the slot
Records of different mutators may contain
Collect the records of all mutators
Get the roots and ZCT of all mutators
All done in an additional collection thread
Snapshooting mutators one by one creates inconsistencies
Handshake: stop a single thread for data exchange
Four handshakes to coordinate with mutators
Use snapshots instead of real heap data
Record updated slots, delayed reference counter updates
Memory overhead: 25% of the heap for snooping, zero count
table and reference counters; 64KB for record buffer
Competitive performance to a stop-the-world mark sweep
collector in the Sun Java VM of 2001
